	"tasks": [
		{
			"uuid": "e745d754-1f2a-4a6b-ae1e-ba88fe9dafd1",
			"title": "DG-28",
			"description": "Task: Fix mobile recovery overlay clipping and overlap.\n\nThe current recovery QTE view does not fit cleanly on the mobile and touch layout. In Scenes/RunScene/RunScene.tscn, the touch steering buttons sit in the lower band of the screen from roughly y=240 to y=344, while the recovery overlay is also anchored into that same lower band with RecoveryMargin spanning roughly y=212 to y=344. The recovery step cards themselves are also built at a fixed 120x88 size in Scenes/RunScene/run_scene.gd. On a landscape mobile-sized view, that causes the recovery panel to sit on top of the touch controls and cuts the prompt row off at the bottom, as shown in the screenshot.\n\nFix this as a layout bug, not as a redesign. The player must be able to see the full recovery title, hint, and prompt row while the touch controls remain usable. Keep the existing recovery flow, input mapping, and overall visual style. The fix should preserve desktop readability while making the touch layout safe on the 640x360 game canvas and common mobile landscape scaling.\n\nAffected files:\n- Scenes/RunScene/RunScene.tscn\n- Scenes/RunScene/run_scene.gd\n- Tests/Unit/test_run_scene.gd\n\nDone when: the full recovery panel is visible during mobile and touch play, the prompt row is no longer clipped at the bottom, the touch buttons remain usable during recovery, desktop layout is not regressed, and automated tests cover the layout constraints.",
			"category": "9509b143-caf2-476d-84d2-062bd75887f9",
			"steps": [
				{
					"details": "Rework the recovery overlay layout so it no longer occupies the same bottom control band as the touch steering buttons. Adjust the RecoveryLayer anchors, panel sizing, and padding so the full recovery panel fits above the touch controls with visible breathing room on the 640x360 layout.\n\nDone when: the recovery title, hint, and prompt row are fully visible on the touch layout and the panel no longer collides with the bottom control area.",
					"done": true
				},
				{
					"details": "Make the recovery prompt presentation responsive enough for the touch layout without changing the recovery mechanic. If needed, reduce recovery panel padding, prompt card minimum size, or prompt font size while recovery is displayed on the touch layout, but keep the current desktop presentation readable.\n\nDone when: the prompt row fits fully inside the panel on the touch layout, the arrow prompts remain readable, and desktop presentation is not materially degraded.",
					"done": true
				},
				{
					"details": "Add automated coverage for the recovery overlay layout during touch and mobile play. Assert that the recovery panel remains inside the viewport, the prompt row is visible, and the panel does not overlap the touch steering buttons in the active recovery state.\n\nDone when: the layout bug is covered by automated tests and the normal verification flow still passes.",
					"done": true
				}
			]
		},
		{
			"uuid": "de1bdeb5-f3cf-4bd7-aa5d-4b565cb58fad",
			"title": "DG-29",
			"description": "Task: Hide touch controls outside mobile and touch contexts.\n\nThe current touch steering and pause buttons in Scenes/RunScene/RunScene.tscn are shown whenever a run is active, regardless of device. That is correct for phones and other touch-first play, but it clutters the desktop experience and contributes to layout pressure when the game is running in a normal non-touch browser or desktop build.\n\nThis ticket should make touch controls context-aware. The buttons should remain available for native mobile builds and for web builds running on touch-capable mobile devices, including a browser on a phone. They should stay hidden on normal desktop builds and desktop browsers without touch input. Keep the current touch button behavior and input wiring once the controls are visible; this ticket is only about when the controls should appear.\n\nUse a runtime visibility rule instead of a separate scene. The touch layer should default to hidden unless the game determines it is in a mobile or touch-capable runtime. For native mobile exports, show the controls immediately. For web builds, show the controls when the runtime reports touch capability, and also allow a first real touch input to reveal them so mobile browsers that delay capability reporting still work. Do not require the player to open a settings menu just to enable touch buttons.\n\nAffected files:\n- Scenes/RunScene/run_scene.gd\n- Tests/Unit/test_run_scene.gd\n\nDone when: touch controls are hidden on desktop and desktop-browser play, visible on native mobile and mobile-browser play, current touch input behavior remains unchanged once visible, and automated tests cover the visibility rules.",
			"category": "9509b143-caf2-476d-84d2-062bd75887f9",
			"steps": [
				{
					"details": "Add a runtime touch-control visibility decision in run_scene.gd that distinguishes desktop play from mobile and touch-capable play. Native mobile builds should show the touch layer immediately. Web builds should show it when touch capability is available and should also be able to reveal it after the first real touch input.\n\nDone when: the touch layer no longer appears during normal desktop play but still appears automatically for the supported mobile and mobile-web cases.",
					"done": true
				},
				{
					"details": "Wire the existing touch-layer refresh flow to use that runtime visibility decision without changing the current touch button input mapping, pause behavior, or recovery-input behavior once the controls are visible.\n\nDone when: touch controls behave exactly as they do now after becoming visible, and only their visibility rules have changed.",
					"done": true
				},
				{
					"details": "Add automated coverage for desktop-hidden behavior, native-mobile-visible behavior, and mobile-web reveal behavior after touch-capability detection or first touch input.\n\nDone when: the visibility rules are covered deterministically and the normal verification flow still passes.",
					"done": true
				}
			]
		},
		{
			"uuid": "d14b0000-0000-0000-0000-000000000014",
			"title": "DG-14",
			"description": "Bug: QTE recovery prompts display ← and → as Unicode arrow characters in Label nodes. These render in the desktop export and local browser testing, but fail on Itch.io — the sandboxed iframe has no accessible system font fallback, so missing glyphs don't render. A prior attempt using Noto Sans Regular also failed: that font simply does not contain those arrow characters (they show as empty boxes in Godot's own glyph map).\n\nThe fix is to use Kenney's input prompts icon font, which is already in the repo at Assets/Art/kenney_input-prompts_1.4.1/Keyboard & Mouse/Fonts/kenney_input_keyboard_&_mouse.ttf. This font uses the Unicode Private Use Area and includes keyboard arrow key glyphs that are guaranteed to be present:\n- keyboard_arrow_left_outline: U+E020\n- keyboard_arrow_right_outline: U+E022\n\nThe outline variants look like physical keyboard key caps, which reads naturally as a QTE prompt. The fix requires placing the font in the project, configuring Godot's import to preload those two PUA glyphs, and updating run_scene.gd to use the font and the correct characters.\n\nDone when: Recovery sequence prompts display keyboard arrow key cap icons in both the web export on Itch.io and the desktop export, with no blank boxes or missing glyphs.",
			"category": "9509b143-caf2-476d-84d2-062bd75887f9",
			"steps": [
				{
					"details": "Copy Assets/Art/kenney_input-prompts_1.4.1/Keyboard & Mouse/Fonts/kenney_input_keyboard_&_mouse.ttf to Assets/Fonts/kenney_input_keyboard_mouse.ttf. Open Godot's Advanced Import Settings for the file (Import tab → Advanced), go to Pre-render Configurations → Glyphs from the Text tab, and paste the two PUA characters (U+E020 and U+E022) into the text field to preload them. Click Reimport.\n\nDone when: Assets/Fonts/kenney_input_keyboard_mouse.ttf exists with a .import sidecar, and the Advanced Import Settings show at least 2 preloaded glyphs with no import errors in the Output log.",
					"done": true
				},
				{
					"details": "In Scenes/RunScene/run_scene.gd, add a preload constant near the top of the file: const ARROW_FONT = preload(\"res://Assets/Fonts/kenney_input_keyboard_mouse.ttf\"). Update _format_recovery_action() to return char(0xE020) for steer_left and char(0xE022) for steer_right. In _build_recovery_step(), add label.add_theme_font_override(\"font\", ARROW_FONT) immediately after the existing add_theme_font_size_override call.\n\nDone when: The script parses without errors, _format_recovery_action() returns the correct PUA characters, and _build_recovery_step() applies the Kenney font to the arrow Label node.",
					"done": true
				}
			]
		},
		{
			"uuid": "d15a0000-0000-0000-0000-000000000015",
			"title": "DG-15",
			"description": "Bug: The player can steer the wagon entirely off the visible road surface into the open desert and bypass all hazards. The lateral clamping system already exists — lateral_position is clamped to ±ROAD_HALF_WIDTH in _process() (line 275 of Scenes/RunScene/run_scene.gd). The problem is that ROAD_HALF_WIDTH is 220.0 (line 29), which is wider than the actual visible road edge. Roadside scrub decorations are placed at ±300, so the wagon can park comfortably in the open desert between the visual road edge and the scrub with no hazard exposure.\n\nThe fix is a one-line constant change. Find the actual road half-width in world units from RunScene.tscn, then tighten ROAD_HALF_WIDTH to match so the clamp aligns with the visible road boundary.\n\nStep 1 note: The visible road polygon in Scenes/RunScene/RunScene.tscn spans x = -180 to x = 180, so the actual road half-width is 180 world units.\n\nDone when: Steering fully left or fully right brings the wagon to the road's visible edge and no further; the open desert is unreachable.",
			"category": "9509b143-caf2-476d-84d2-062bd75887f9",
			"steps": [
				{
					"details": "Open RunScene.tscn in Godot and locate the road background node. Check its width to determine the road's actual half-width in world units. If the road is a ColorRect or Polygon2D, read its size or polygon extents directly.\n\nDone when: The road's actual half-width in world units is known and documented in the commit message or step notes.",
					"done": true
				},
				{
					"details": "In Scenes/RunScene/run_scene.gd line 29, update ROAD_HALF_WIDTH from 220.0 to the value found in Step 1 (or the closest value confirmed by in-editor playtesting). Steer fully left and right in-editor to confirm the wagon reaches the road edge without entering the desert.\n\nDone when: Fully left or right steering brings the wagon to the visual road edge; the desert area cannot be reached during normal gameplay.",
					"done": true
				}
			]
		},
		{
			"uuid": "d16a0000-0000-0000-0000-000000000016",
			"title": "DG-16",
			"description": "Task: The game is keyboard-only and unplayable on mobile browsers. Since Godot maps screen taps to mouse events in web exports, the menu buttons and onboarding dismissal already work on mobile. What's missing is in-game steering and a pause trigger.\n\nThe fix is three clickable buttons added to a dedicated CanvasLayer:\n- Left arrow — anchored bottom-left. Wires button_down → Input.action_press(\"steer_left\") and button_up → Input.action_release(\"steer_left\") so the wagon steers continuously while held, matching keyboard hold behavior.\n- Right arrow — mirror of the left button, bottom-right, wires steer_right.\n- Pause — anchored top-right corner, calls _set_pause_state(true) directly (Escape key doesn't exist on mobile).\n\nThe steering buttons must use button_down/button_up (not pressed) because Input.get_axis() in _process() requires the action to be held, not just pulsed. The existing _set_pause_state() function in run_scene.gd handles the pause toggle cleanly.\n\nProject display settings also need to be configured — currently project.godot has no viewport size, stretch mode, or orientation set.\n\nAffected files:\n- project.godot\n- Scenes/RunScene/RunScene.tscn\n- Scenes/RunScene/run_scene.gd\n\nDone when: On a mobile browser in landscape orientation, the player can steer left and right using the on-screen buttons, pause via the top-right button, and all existing menu/result/onboarding interactions continue to work via tap.",
			"category": "9509b143-caf2-476d-84d2-062bd75887f9",
			"steps": [
				{
					"details": "In project.godot, set the display window size to 1152x648, stretch mode to canvas_items, stretch aspect to keep, and orientation to landscape. These settings ensure the game scales correctly to any screen size without distorting the viewport.\n\nDone when: project.godot contains explicit display/window size, stretch mode, stretch aspect, and orientation settings; the game renders correctly at non-native resolutions in the editor.",
					"done": true
				},
				{
					"details": "In RunScene.tscn, add a new CanvasLayer node named TouchLayer as a sibling of HUDLayer. Inside it, add three Button nodes: TouchLeft (anchored bottom-left), TouchRight (anchored bottom-right), TouchPause (anchored top-right). Size them at minimum 80x80 px. Style them as flat/transparent with simple arrow and pause glyphs so they don't obscure gameplay.\n\nDone when: All three buttons appear in the running scene at their correct corners and do not obscure the road or HUD.",
					"done": true
				},
				{
					"details": "In run_scene.gd, add @onready references for TouchLeft, TouchRight, and TouchPause. Wire TouchLeft and TouchRight using Input.parse_input_event() with a synthetic InputEventAction rather than Input.action_press() directly — this injects a real event into the pipeline so both _process() (steering via get_axis) and _input() (QTE recovery via is_action_pressed) pick it up. On button_down, parse a pressed=true InputEventAction for the relevant action; on button_up, parse a pressed=false event. Wire TouchPause pressed → _set_pause_state(true). Ensure both steer actions are released in _exit_tree() so held state doesn't leak across scenes. No separate QTE button handling is needed — tapping TouchLeft/TouchRight during a recovery sequence naturally satisfies the QTE prompt.\n\nDone when: Clicking and holding TouchLeft/TouchRight steers the wagon continuously; releasing stops steering. Tapping either button during a recovery sequence counts as QTE input. Clicking TouchPause opens the pause menu. Keyboard controls are unaffected.",
					"done": true
				}
			]
		},
		{
			"uuid": "23aa4f3e-0446-4cca-a319-08e3bca9dc98",
			"title": "DG-1",
			"description": "Task: Game shell and driving core.\nGoal: Create the first playable slice with a main run scene, wagon controller, camera framing, and scrolling road.\nEnd state: The player can launch the project, start driving immediately, steer left/right, and stay centered in a readable top-down road view.\nOut of scope for this ticket: hazards, failures, results, polish.",
			"category": "9509b143-caf2-476d-84d2-062bd75887f9",
